  "prompt": "What is the salary of a cosmologist?",
  "response": "The salary of a cosmologist can vary widely based on factors such as education, experience, geographic location, employer type (academia, government, private sector), and specific role within the field. Here\u2019s a general overview:\n\n### 1. **Entry-Level Positions (e.g., Postdoctoral Researcher)**\n   - **Salary Range:** $50,000 to $70,000 per year.\n   - Postdocs typically work in academic or research institutions while gaining experience and publications.\n\n### 2. **Mid-Career Positions (e.g., Research Scientist, Assistant Professor)**\n   - **Salary Range:** $70,000 to $120,000 per year.\n   - These roles often require a PhD and several years of experience in research or teaching.\n\n### 3. **Senior-Level Positions (e.g., Tenured Professor, Senior Researcher)**\n   - **Salary Range:** $100,000 to $150,000 or more per year.\n   - High-level positions in academia, national labs, or private research organizations command higher salaries.\n\n### 4. **Government and Private Sector Roles**\n   - **Salary Range:** $80,000 to $150,000+ per year.\n   - Cosmologists working for government agencies (e.g., NASA) or private companies may earn higher salaries, especially in specialized or leadership roles.\n\n### 5. **Geographic Location**\n   - Salaries tend to be higher in countries or regions with a strong focus on scientific research, such as the United States, Western Europe, or Japan.\n   - Cost of living in the area also influences salary levels.\n\n### 6. **Additional Factors**\n   - Grants, publications, and prestige in the field can impact earning potential.\n   - Cosmologists may also earn additional income through consulting, writing, or speaking engagements.\n\n### Average Salary Range\n   - **Overall Average:** $80,000 to $120,000 per year, depending on the above factors.\n\nFor more specific salary information, it\u2019s helpful to consult industry reports, job postings, or networking with professionals in the field.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
